<strong>The lecture notes are a collaborative effort of the participants in the course. You are not required to contribute to the lecture notes, but are encouraged to do so. Together, we can create resources that will be helpful to everyone.</strong></p>
<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="Notes_for_Week_4:_4.1_Definition_of_Price_Elasticity_of_Supply">Notes for Week 4: 4.1 Definition of Price Elasticity of Supply</span></h2>
<p>Price elasticity of SUPPLY for $$E&#95;x =\cfrac{\% change Q&#95;X}{\% change P&#95;X} = \cfrac{\% ∆ Q&#95;x }{\% ∆ P&#95;x}$$</p>
<p><a href="/wiki/images/a/af/4.4_Price_Elasticity_of_Supply.png" class="image"><img alt="4.4 Price Elasticity of Supply.png" src="/wiki/images/a/af/4.4_Price_Elasticity_of_Supply.png" width="428" height="544" /></a>
<ul><li> Inelastic: Change in price results in small change in quantity
</li><li> Elastic: Small change in price results in large changes in quantity</p>
</li></ul>

<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id=""><br /></span></h2>
<p><br />
Examples:
PX = 10%        EX = (% ∆ Qx )/(% ∆ Px) = (-5)/10 = -0.5
QX = 5%</p>
<p>PX = 10%        EX = (% ∆ Qx )/(% ∆ Px) = (-15)/10 = -1.5
QX = 15%</p>
<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="_2"><br /></span></h2>
<p><br />
<ul><li> Classification:
</li></ul>
 * Elastic (very responsive) = absolute value of E &gt; 1
 * Inelastic (not very responsive) = absolute value of E &lt; 1, 
 * Unitary = absolute value of E = 1</p>

